]]>
<![CDATA[
wn hall</a> on Thursday, Zuckerberg theorized the Rift will lose its visor-like appearance and eventually resemble a pair of glasses. Facebook purchased Oculus, the company developing Rift, for US$2 billion last year.</p><p>Eventually, the headset won’t need to be tethered to a computer to work, so people can move around freely while wearing it, Zuckerberg said.</p><p>Instead of pulling out a smartphone to share pictures with friends, people will use their virtual reality glasses to open photo albums, resize images and view them through the headsets, he said.</p><p class="jumpTag"><a href="/article/2923272/zuckerberg-sees-oculus-rift-shrinking-to-the-size-of-glasses.html#jump">To read this article in full or to leave a comment, please click here</a></p></section></article>
